                        <additions>
                            <list>
                                <item xml:id="a1">
                                    <locus from="1v" to="4"/>
                                    <locus target="172v"/>
                                    <desc type="GuestText"><title type="complete" ref="LIT2736RepCh20"/>
                                    The complete <foreign xml:lang="gez-tr">Malkəʾa Śəllāse</foreign> has been written
                                        on flyleaves, the first part upside-down on <locus from="1v" to="1r">fol. 1v followed by 1r</locus>,
                                        then the end (including what appears to be a <foreign xml:lang="gez-tr">tarafa malkəʾ</foreign>)
                                        on <locus from="193rb" to="193va"/>.
                                        <bibl><ptr target="bm:Loefgren1974Katalog"/><citedRange unit="page">45</citedRange>
                                        notes that it consists of 45 rhymed stanzas and gives the first two stanzas. He notes that
                                        one <foreign xml:lang="gez-tr">Nəguś</foreign> ʾIyāsu is mentioned in the 
                                            <foreign xml:lang="gez-tr">malkəʾ</foreign> and thus concludes that it was
                                            written either under 
                                            <persName ref="PRS5616IyasuI">ʾIyāsu I (1682–1706)</persName> or
                                            <persName ref="PRS5617IyasuII">ʾIyāsu II (1730–1755)</persName>.
                                            The <foreign xml:lang="gez-tr">tarafa malkəʾ</foreign> is analysed as a
                                            "<foreign xml:lang="gez-tr">səbḥat</foreign> hymn in 7 three-line stanzas"
                                            ("<foreign xml:lang="de"><foreign xml:lang="gez-tr">Sebḥat</foreign>-Hymne
                                                in 7 dreizeiligen Strophen</foreign>") and its incipit is reproduced.</bibl>
                                    </desc>
                                </item>
                            </list>
                        </additions>
                        
